The goal of CRISPR-Cas9 is to identify specific segments in the organisms' DNA, called promoters, which generate a responsive transcript in the DNA. When the targeted promoter is located in a relatively stable part of the gene, it can be easily replaced with other responses, but if it is in an independent segment, it may lead to the death of the organism.

### Potential Applications

CRISPR-Cas9 has many potential applications in the medical field. One of them is the development of drugs that can treat autoimmune diseases. Other possibilities include:

- Blocking diseases such as cancer and other tumor diseases;
- Eliminating congenital and genetically determined diseases;
- Effective immune therapy to prevent infections;
- Achieving a cheap life;
- Inserting an additional gene to improve human function or appearance.

